Question 3: Apply regression analysis to the dataset to predict AmountSpent

  • Run a multiple linear regression model. How does it perform?

This model indicates that the predictor variables account for 79% of the variance in the AmountSpent variable.

market_origin <- market
market <- dummy_cols(market)
market <- market[c(names(market[10:32]),"Salary")]

normalize <- function(x) { 
    x <- as.matrix(x)
    minAttr=apply(x, 2, min)
    maxAttr=apply(x, 2, max)
    x <- sweep(x, 2, minAttr, FUN="-") 
    x=sweep(x, 2,  maxAttr-minAttr, "/") 
    return (x)
} 

market$AmountSpent <- normalize(market$AmountSpent)
market$Salary <- normalize(market$Salary)

m1 <- lm(AmountSpent~., data = market)

Question 4: Apply polynomial and locfit to the analysis

  • Apply a polynomial model to the dataset to predict AmountSpent. How does it perform? How did you choose your parameters?

I use For-loop to calculate RSS for each degree from 1 to 30, and the result is that degree 4 has the smallest RSS, therefore, I choose degree 4 as the best parameter.

The residual standard error is 0.1111, multiple R-squared is 0.4922, adjusted R-squared is 0.4902, F-statistic is 241.1, and p-value is less than 2.2e-16.

polynomial = function(feature, power){
    return(data.frame(sapply(1:power, function(x){(feature)**x})))
}

for (i in 1:30) {
    dat = polynomial(market_train_tbl$Salary, i)
    dat$AmountSpent = market_train_tbl$AmountSpent
    model = lm(AmountSpent~., data = dat)

    valid_dat = polynomial(market_test_tbl$Salary, i)
    rss = sum((market_test_tbl$AmountSpent - predict.lm(model, newdata = valid_dat))**2)
    print(paste(c("Degree: ", i, " RSS: ", rss), collapse=""))
}
